---
import DocsLayout from '../../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import Callout from '../../../../components/Callout.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../../../../components/CodeBlock.astro';
import Checklist from '../../../../components/Checklist.astro';
---

<DocsLayout title="Deployment" description="Deployment IS the Terraform workflow — terraform plan is the PR, terraform apply is the deploy, and CI/CD automates it.">
  <h1 class="mb-6">Deployment</h1>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">This is the deployment project. Everything you've been building — Terraform configuration, Docker containers, Nginx setup — culminates here. But unlike previous projects where deployment was "push to Netlify" or "deploy to Railway," deployment for P6 is the Terraform workflow itself. <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">terraform plan</code> is the PR. <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">terraform apply</code> is the deploy.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">The Terraform deployment workflow</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">The deployment process mirrors the PR process you already know:</p>

  <div class="space-y-4 mb-8">
    <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-base font-semibold mb-2"><code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">terraform plan</code> = the PR</h3>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">Shows what will change. You review the plan like you review a diff. "This will create 1 EC2 instance and 1 security group." You read it, verify it matches your intent, and either approve or revise.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-base font-semibold mb-2"><code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">terraform apply</code> = the deploy</h3>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">Executes the plan. Creates, updates, or destroys resources in AWS. Once applied, the infrastructure exists. This is the "merge" moment — the change is live.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Infrastructure deployment</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">If you haven't already applied your Terraform configuration during the building phase, now is the time. From the <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">/infra</code> directory:</p>

  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`$ cd infra
$ terraform plan
# Review the plan — what's being created? Any surprises?

$ terraform apply
# Type "yes" when prompted — this creates real AWS resources`}</CodeBlock>

  <p class="text-text-secondary mt-4 mb-4">After apply completes, Terraform outputs the EC2 public IP, S3 bucket name, and any other configured outputs. Note these — you'll need them for the next steps.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Application deployment</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">With the EC2 instance running, deploy the application containers:</p>

  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`# SSH into the EC2 instance
$ ssh -i ~/.ssh/your-key.pem ec2-user@<ec2-public-ip>

# Pull the latest code
$ cd ~/tidal-brewing
$ git pull origin main

# Start the containers
$ docker compose up -d --build

# Verify containers are running
$ docker ps
# Should show: frontend, backend, database, nginx

# Run database migrations
$ docker compose exec backend alembic upgrade head

# Seed the database with initial data
$ docker compose exec backend python seed.py

# Verify from the outside (on your local machine)
$ curl http://<ec2-public-ip>
# Should return the Tidal Brewing homepage`}</CodeBlock>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">SSL setup</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">HTTPS is not optional for a site that takes orders — even without payment processing, the form collects names and phone numbers. Set up Let's Encrypt via certbot on the EC2 instance:</p>

  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`# On the EC2 instance
$ sudo yum install -y certbot python3-certbot-nginx
$ sudo certbot --nginx -d your-domain.com

# Verify auto-renewal
$ sudo certbot renew --dry-run`}</CodeBlock>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>You need a domain name for SSL.</strong> Let's Encrypt issues certificates to domain names, not IP addresses. Register a domain (or use a free subdomain service) and point it to your EC2 public IP. Without a domain, you can run on HTTP for testing — but HTTPS is required before Jake uses it.</p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Secrets in production</h2>
  <Callout variant="warning">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>No .env files on the server.</strong> Production secrets live in AWS Secrets Manager:</p>
    <ul class="text-sm space-y-1 mt-2">
      <li><code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">DATABASE_URL</code> — PostgreSQL connection string</li>
      <li><code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">ADMIN_PASSWORD</code> — Jake's admin password (hashed in the database, but the initial seed needs it)</li>
      <li>Any API keys added later</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="text-sm mt-2">The application retrieves secrets from AWS Secrets Manager at startup. This is configured in the Docker entrypoint or application startup script.</p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">CI/CD for infrastructure</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Automate the Terraform workflow with GitHub Actions. The same CI/CD concepts from previous projects, applied to infrastructure:</p>

  <div class="space-y-4 mb-8">
    <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-base font-semibold mb-2">On pull request: <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">terraform plan</code></h3>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">When a PR changes <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">.tf</code> files, GitHub Actions runs <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">terraform plan</code> and posts the output as a PR comment. You review the plan alongside the code diff. This is the infrastructure equivalent of running tests on a PR.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-base font-semibold mb-2">On merge to main: <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">terraform apply</code></h3>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">When a PR is merged to main, GitHub Actions runs <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">terraform apply</code> with auto-approve. The infrastructure is updated automatically. This is the infrastructure equivalent of auto-deploying on merge.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <Callout variant="warning">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Auto-apply is powerful and dangerous.</strong> Once you set up <code>terraform apply</code> on merge, every merged PR that changes .tf files will modify your live infrastructure. This is why the plan review on the PR is critical — it's your last chance to catch mistakes before they're applied to production.</p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Deployment verification</h2>
  <Checklist items={[
    "The live URL loads the Tidal Brewing homepage",
    "The tap list displays current beers on tap",
    "The events page shows upcoming events",
    "The pickup order form submits successfully",
    "Jake can log into the admin interface",
    "Jake can add, update, and remove beers from the tap list",
    "Jake can create and edit events",
    "Jake can view pickup orders and mark them as packed/picked up",
    "HTTPS is active — browser shows the lock icon",
    "Beer images load from S3",
  ]} />

  <details class="mb-8 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary class="px-4 py-3 cursor-pointer font-semibold text-sm bg-bg-muted">Troubleshooting: "terraform apply succeeded but the site doesn't load"</summary>
    <div class="p-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2">Common causes:</p>
      <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-1">
        <li>Docker containers aren't running — SSH in and check <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">docker ps</code></li>
        <li>Nginx isn't configured or isn't running — check <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">systemctl status nginx</code> or <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">docker logs nginx</code></li>
        <li>Security group doesn't allow port 80/443 — check in AWS console</li>
        <li>Application crashed on startup — check <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">docker logs &lt;container-name&gt;</code></li>
        <li>Secrets Manager not accessible — check IAM role on the EC2 instance</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mt-2">SSH into the instance and debug from the inside out. Start with <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">docker ps</code> — if containers aren't running, nothing else matters.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <details class="my-8 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary class="px-6 py-4 bg-bg-muted cursor-pointer font-semibold text-sm">The landscape: CI/CD for infrastructure</summary>
    <div class="px-6 py-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4">We use GitHub Actions running <code>terraform plan</code> and <code>terraform apply</code>. Here's what else exists for infrastructure CI/CD.</p>
      <div class="space-y-3">
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">GitHub Actions + Terraform</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">What we use. Runs plan on PR, apply on merge. Simple to set up with the hashicorp/setup-terraform action. Works well for small teams.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Atlantis</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Open-source Terraform automation. Runs as a server, listens for PR webhooks, runs plan automatically, posts the output as a PR comment. Apply via PR comment (<code>atlantis apply</code>). Popular in teams that want Terraform CI/CD without writing their own GitHub Actions workflows.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Spacelift</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">SaaS platform for Terraform CI/CD. Managed plan/apply, drift detection, policy enforcement, approval workflows. More features than DIY GitHub Actions, but adds a vendor dependency and cost.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Terraform Cloud</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">HashiCorp's own CI/CD for Terraform. Remote state management, plan/apply workflows, team collaboration. Free tier covers small teams. Natural choice if you're already invested in HashiCorp tools.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">env0</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">SaaS platform for infrastructure automation. Supports Terraform, Pulumi, and others. Cost estimation, policy enforcement, self-service environments. Similar to Spacelift with additional cost management features.</span></p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mt-4">GitHub Actions is the simplest starting point — you're already using it for application CI/CD. Atlantis is the common next step when the team grows. Terraform Cloud or Spacelift for larger organisations that need governance and approval workflows.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <div class="mt-8 p-6 bg-primary-bg rounded-lg border border-primary/20 text-center">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-2">Next: UAT</h2>
    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Deployed and verified. Time to show Jake.</p>
    <a
      href="/web-dev/projects/6/uat"
      class="inline-block bg-primary hover:bg-primary-dark text-white font-semibold py-3 px-6 rounded-md transition-colors min-h-[44px]"
    >
      UAT →
    </a>
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
